06214nam a22008535i 9781526121523DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172000xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815261215237 a10.7765/97815261215232doi  a(DE-B1597)660134  a(OCoLC)1232701917  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB 4aDT1896 7aHIS0470002bisacsh04a968.0482211 aLowry, Donal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe South African War reappraised /cDonal Lowry. 1aManchester : bManchester University Press, c[2017] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Imperialism ;v3600tFront matter -- tContents -- tGeneral editor’s introduction -- tNotes on contributors -- tAcknowledgements -- t1 Introduction -- t2 A century of controversy over origins -- t3 Journalism as active politics -- t4 The Times at war, 1899–1902 -- t5 ‘Intermediate’ imperialism and the test of Empire -- t6 Boer attitudes to Africans in wartime -- t7 The Cape Afrikaners and the British Empire from the Jameson Raid to the South African War -- t8 African attitudes to Britain and the Empire before and after the South African War -- t9 ‘Hamlet with the Prince of Denmark left out’? -- t10 Pricking the ‘non-conformist conscience’ -- t11 Kruger’s farmers, Strathcona’s Horse, Sir George Clarke’s camels and the Kaiser’s battleships -- t12 ‘The Boers were the beginning of the end’? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe neo-classical troopers&apos; memorial of New Zealand, together with others around the former British Empire, illustrates the manner in which the South African War became a major imperial. This book explores how South Africa is negotiating its past in and through various modes of performance in contemporary theatre, public events and memorial spaces. Opinion on the war was as divided among white Afrikaners, Africans, &apos;Coloureds&apos; and English-speaking white South Africans as these communities were from each other. The book analyses the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) as a live event and as an archive asking throughout how the TRC has affected the definition of identity and memory in contemporary South Africa, including disavowed memories. It surveys a century of controversy surrounding the origins of the war and in particular the argument that gold shaped British policy towards the Transvaal in the drift towards war. The remarkable South African career of Flora Shaw, the first woman to gain a professional position on The Times, is portrayed in the book. The book also examines the expensive operation mounted by The Times in order to cover the war. While acknowledging the need not to overstress the role of personality, the book echoes J. A. S. Grenville in describing the combination of Milner and Chamberlain as a &apos;fateful partnership&apos;. Current renegotiations of popular repertoires, particularly songs and dances related to the struggle, revivals of classic European and South African protest plays, new history plays and specific racial and ethnic histories and identities, are analysed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSouth African War, 1899-1902. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / Republic of South Africa.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aBritish policy.  aChamberlain.  aMilner.  aNew Zealand.  aSouth African War.  aTransvaal.  aTruth and Reconciliation Commission.  acontemporary theatre.  aethnic histories.  agold.  amemorial spaces.  apopular repertoires.  aprotest plays.  apublic events.  aracial histories.1 aBeaumont, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenyon, 